# Frontend: Svelte

## Component Structure
- Use SvelteKit for full-stack apps; standalone Svelte for widget-style embeds
- One component per `.svelte` file; name files in `PascalCase`
- Keep components under 200 lines; extract child components when growing
- Use `<script lang="ts">` for TypeScript support

## Reactivity (Svelte 5 Runes)
- Use `$state()` for reactive state declarations
- Use `$derived()` for computed values (replaces `$:` reactive statements)
- Use `$effect()` for side effects (replaces `$:` blocks with side effects)
- Use `$props()` for component props with type safety
- Avoid mutating state outside of the component that owns it

## SvelteKit Patterns
- Use `+page.svelte` and `+page.server.ts` for page components and data loading
- Use `+layout.svelte` for shared UI (nav, footer)
- Use `+server.ts` for API routes
- Use `load` functions for data fetching — avoid client-side fetching when SSR is available
- Use form actions for mutations; progressive enhancement with `use:enhance`

## State Management
- Use Svelte stores (`writable`, `readable`, `derived`) for shared state
- Prefer `$state()` runes in Svelte 5 over stores for local state
- Use context API (`setContext`/`getContext`) for dependency injection
- Keep stores small and domain-specific; avoid a single global store

## Performance
- SvelteKit handles code splitting per route automatically
- Use `{#key}` blocks to force re-render when data identity changes
- Use `{#each items as item (item.id)}` with keys for list performance
- Lazy-load heavy components with dynamic `import()`

## Testing
- Use `@testing-library/svelte` for component tests
- Use Playwright for E2E tests with SvelteKit
- Test component behavior via user interactions, not internal state
- Mock `fetch` or use MSW for API mocking in tests

## Conventions
- Follow SvelteKit file-based routing conventions
- Use TypeScript in all `.svelte` files
- Use CSS scoping (default in Svelte); use `:global()` sparingly
- Use `svelte-check` in CI for type and lint validation
